{{Distinguish|Abrogation (disambiguation)}}

{{canon law}}
In the [[canon law (Catholic Church)|canon law]] of the [[Catholic Church]], '''obrogation''' is the enacting of a contrary law that is a revocation of a previous law.<ref>Della Rocca, ''Manual'', 69.</ref> It may also be the partial cancellation or amendment of a law, decree, or legal regulation by the imposition of a newer one.

==Obrogation==
In the [[Civil law (legal system)|civil law]], obrogation is the modification or repeal of a law in whole or in part by issuing a new law.<ref>{{cite book |title=Obrogate |work=[[Merriam-Webster Dictionary]] |publisher=Merriam-Webster.com. |accessdate=March 24, 2016 |url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/obrogate}}{{subscription}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=obrogate |work=[[Black's Law Dictionary]] |edition=7th |page=1104 |first1=Bryan A. |last1=Garner |authorlink1=Bryan A. Garner |publisher=[[West Publishing]] |location=St. Paul, Minnesota |year=1999 |isbn=0-314-22864-0}}</ref>

The [[1983 Code of Canon Law]] governs here in Canon 53: {{quote|If decrees are contrary one to another, where specific matters are expressed, the specific prevails over the general; if both are equally specific or equally general, the one later in time<ref name=Can53/> obrogates ([[Ecclesiastical Latin|Latin]]: ''obrogat''<ref>Caparros ''et al.'', ''[[1983 Code of Canon Law]] Annotated'', canon 53 (pg. 66)</ref> from ''obrogare''{{sfn|Black|Nolan|Connolly|1979|page=971}}) the earlier insofar as it is contrary to it.<ref name=Can53>[[1983 Code of Canon Law]], [http://www.intratext.com/IXT/ENG0017/_P6.HTM Canon 53], accessed 24 March 2016</ref>}}

This canon incorporates Rule 34 in VI of the ''[[Regulae Iuris]]'': ''"Generi per speciem derogatur"'' or "The specific derogates from the general."<ref>Coriden ''et al.'', ''Commentary'', pg. 54 (commentary on canon 53).</ref>

